utting the molding to 225deg.";i:39;s:46:"And several other options and its not working.";i:40;s:61:"Often to the top where its thicker lines up but theres a gap.";i:41;s:133:"Chair rail is available in a variety of woods and styles from inexpensive paint-grade pine to large very expensive hardwood profiles.";i:42;s:88:"You can also make your own chair rail molding with standard trim or clear 1-by material.";i:43;s:55:"The special-order cherry molding we used cost 5 per ft.";i:44;s:98:"To cut the chair rail youll need a miter saw and a coping saw with extra blades they break easily.";i:45;s:21:"A finish nailer isnt.";i:46;s:94:"The inside corner cuts on your chair rail must be made different than the outside corner cuts.";i:47;s:90:"Insert the rail into the miter box with its front face touching the back of the miter box.";i:48;s:59:"In cutting the molding try to cut the smaller pieces first.";i:49;s:41:"Adjust the Miter Saw and Cut the Molding.";i:50;s:154:"Set the miter saw to 41 degrees left and cut the first piece of crown molding in the demonstration then readjust to 41 degrees right for the second piece.";i:51;s:42:"Join the pieces for the inside work angle.";i:52;s:27:"Cutting Chair Rail Corners.";i:53;s:49:"Select appropriate molding to be your chair rail.";i:54;s:43:"Mark and cut the molding using a miter saw.";i:55;s:69:"Miter the end of another piece of molding or scrap then cut off only.";i:56;s:79:"Put the crown corner into place and then nail it off with the pneumatic nailer.";i:57;s:27:"When installing chair rail.";i:58;s:61:"Take the height of your chair rail to the baseboard or floor.";i:59;s:22:"My height was 43 34in.";i:60;s:67:"I subtracted 10in 2 x 5in for the spaces above and below the boxes.";i:61;s:63:"And also subtracted 13125x2 for the thickness of 2 trim pieces.";i:62;s:100:"This gave me the measurement for the vertical pieces of the box which I also needed 6 of these cuts.";i:63;s:128:"I am Mark Clement licensed contractor and tool expert here today to show you how to cope various moldings using the Dremel tool.";i:64;s:50:"Now I am going to show you how to cope chair rail.";i:65;s:79:"Now all coped joints start with an inside miter which we make on the miter saw.";i:66;s:21:"Set it to 45 degrees.";i:67;s:29:"We are going to make the cut.";i:68;s:185:"To install the molding apply wood glue or construction adhesive to the back of the first piece and attach it to the wall placing the bottom edge of the wood at the guideline you marked.";}}